  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2020136622" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2020136622" />
    <a title="Donna" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/6217162-donna"><img alt="Donna" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1430955688p2/6217162.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2020136622?book_show_action=true">Aug 20, 2017</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Donna" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Donna" href="/user/show/6217162-donna">Donna</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/6217162-donna?shelf=criminal-mystery">criminal-mystery</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2020136622" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer14700576926863696866">And Connelly hits one out of the ballpark again. How does he do it? How does he consistently produce such great stories throughout such a long writing career? It helps that he writes with as much authenticity and integrity as his characters possess. And his latest character in his newest series is no exception. <br/><br/>Renée Ballard is a young detective with 14 years of her life invested in the LA Police Department, only to see it practically go down the drain when she files sexual harassment charges ag</span>
  <span id="freeText14700576926863696866" style="display:none">And Connelly hits one out of the ballpark again. How does he do it? How does he consistently produce such great stories throughout such a long writing career? It helps that he writes with as much authenticity and integrity as his characters possess. And his latest character in his newest series is no exception. <br /><br />Renée Ballard is a young detective with 14 years of her life invested in the LA Police Department, only to see it practically go down the drain when she files sexual harassment charges against her commander. Rather than receive justice in the matter, despite there being a witness who unfortunately never came to her defense, she was punished for making waves and was assigned to working "The Late Show" which is the 11 pm to 7 am shift. Besides the crummy hours, what's worse is the lack of satisfaction during that shift when detectives may start investigations, but must turn most of them over to the day crew to follow up with and eventually solve. That's because detectives can't exactly interview people, gather clues and process them during those late and early morning hours and expect any results. But two cases Renée catches at night she refuses to let go of during the day because the victims either aren't deemed important enough to have priority or are seen as collateral damage in the larger scheme of things. Always seeking justice for the underdog as she is one herself, Renée forgoes sleep and deepens her investigations even though she has been told to stand back and stand down. And she soon discovers when continuing on that she stands to lose more than sleep as her investigations grow increasingly complicated and connect to more than she ever could have bargained for when beginning them. <br /><br />I'm a long time fan of Connelly and have read and enjoyed just about every book he has written, so it's no surprise I enjoyed this book, too. I was certainly excited to begin a new series by him, especially one featuring a female protagonist this time. Not that I haven't enjoyed reading mainly about male characters in his other series, but I was curious to see how he would develop a main female character this time when females have always played such a minor role in his other stories. So when I first started reading this book with its competent yet impulsive maverick of a detective who went off on her own against orders, I was a little disappointed because I couldn't helping thinking of her as just a female version of Harry Bosch. But soon, Connelly deftly revealed a bit more about Ballard with each new chapter and she grew into her unique self, her tragic childhood and professional background making her into a sympathetic character the reader can care about, one who is well in control of her emotions until she isn't and zings the reader right in the heart. <br /><br />As for the story, there are multiple criminal mysteries within it which have enough turns and ultimately twists to keep those pages moving through the reader's fingers. And there were plenty of heart stopping and jaw dropping moments, including the very ending with its emotional punch that made my chest ache. I only had one quibble about this book which troubled me. It was the pervasive use of female characters as victims which you may not think is unusual in a criminal mystery series. But I felt repeated instances where it occurred with sexual components was too much and it set off warning bells for me. So I hope this isn't a sign of things to come in this series. If it is, you'll hear about it from me. But aside from that, I enjoyed every bit of this book with its wonderful new main character I'd enjoy reading more about. <br /><br />What else can I say? If you've never read anything by this author, go ahead and start here as it's the first in a new series. Then start at the beginning of his other two series while waiting for more of this one. You'll have a lot of catching up to do and many pleasurable reading hours ahead of you while doing it. But if you're already a fan of Connelly, you're already all caught up in more ways than one, and you didn't need me to convince you this book would be a winner and a must read. Connelly's track record precedes him and speaks for itself, louder than any number of five star reviews.</span>
  <a data-text-id="14700576926863696866" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


